[[Image:Olympic flame at opening ceremony.jpg|thumb|The [[Olympic flame]] burns in the [[Athens Olympic Stadium]] cauldron, during the opening ceremonies of the [[2004 Summer Olympics]].]]
[[Image:Galfridman.jpg|thumb|[[Gal Fridman]] won [[Israel at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Israel's]] first ever Olympic gold medal in the [[Sailing at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Men's sailboard|sailboard event]], during the [[2004 Summer Olympics]].]]

The '''2004 Summer Olympics medal count''' is a list of [[National Olympic Committees]] ranked by the number of [[medal]]s won during the [[2004 Summer Olympics]], held in [[Athens]], [[Greece]], from [[August 13]] to [[August 29]], [[2004]]. A total of 10,625&nbsp;athletes from 201&nbsp;countries participated in these games, competing in 301&nbsp;events in 28&nbsp;sports. [[Kiribati]] and [[Timor Leste]] competed for the first time in these [[Olympic Games]].<ref name="olympic.org">{{cite web | title =  Athens 2004&ndash;Games of the XXVIII Olympiad | publisher = International Olympic Committee | url = http://www.olympic.org/uk/games/past/index_uk.asp?OLGT=1&OLGY=2004 | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}</ref>

Athletes from 74&nbsp;countries won at least one medal, leaving 127&nbsp;countries without a medal. The [[United States]] won the most medals overall (102), as well as the most gold (36) and silver (39) medals, while the [[Russia|Russian Federation]] won the most bronze medals (38). Host nation [[Greece]] finished the games with sixteen medals overall (six gold, six silver, and four bronze).<ref name="medal count"> {{cite web | title =  Athens 2004&ndash;Medal Table | publisher = International Olympic Committee | url = http://www.olympic.org/uk/games/past/table_uk.asp?OLGT=1&OLGY=2004 | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}</ref> [[Israel at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Israel]] and the [[United Arab Emirates at the 2004 Summer Olympics|United Arab Emirates]] won Olympic gold medals for the first time in their history.<ref name="olympicdyk">{{cite web | title =  Athens 2004&ndash;Did You Know? | publisher = International Olympic Committee | url = http://www.olympic.org/uk/games/past/innovations_uk.asp?OLGT=1&OLGY=2004 | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Associated Press | title =Windsurfer wins Israel's first gold | work =ESPN.com | date =[[August 25]], [[2004]] | url =http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer04/sailing/news/story?id=1867247 | accessdate =2008-05-05}}</ref>

==Changes in medal standings==
Since the closure of these games, [[Scandals of the 2004 Summer Olympics|doping scandals]] have resulted in the stripping of medals from a number of athletes, thus affecting the medal standings. Greek [[weightlifting|weightlifter]] [[Leonidas Sampanis]] was the first, losing his bronze medal in the [[Weightlifting at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Men's 62 kg|men's 62 kg competition]], so fourth placed [[Venezuela|Venezuelan]] [[Israel Jose Rubio]] received the medal in his place. Russian athlete [[Irina Korzhanenko]] lost her gold medal in [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Women's shot put|women's shot put]], with [[Cuba]]n [[Yumileidi Cumb<U+00E1>|Yumileidi Cumb<U+00E1> Jay]] replacing her as the Olympic champion, [[Germany|German]] [[Nadine Kleinert]] receiving the silver medal, and [[Svetlana Krivelyova]] of Russia receiving the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web | last =Associated Press | title =Ancient Olympia's First Female Winner Stripped of Medal | work =USA Today | date =[[August 23]], [[2004]] | url =http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/athens/track/2004-08-23-shotput-stripped_x.htm
| accessdate =2008-05-05}}</ref> 
[[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Robert Fazekas]] was stripped of his gold medal in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Men's discus throw|men's discus throw]], shifting the gold medal to [[Virgilijus Alekna]] of [[Lithuania]], the silver medal to [[Zoltan Kovago]] of Hungary, and the bronze medal to [[Aleksander Tammert]] of [[Estonia]].<ref>{{cite web | last =Reuters | title =Discus Champion Thrown out of Games After Doping Breach | work =ABC News Online| date =[[August 25]], [[2004]] | url =http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200408/s1184357.htm
| accessdate =2008-05-05}}</ref> [[Adrian Annus]], also from Hungary, was stripped of the gold medal in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Men's hammer throw|men's hammer throw]], handing the Olympic title to [[Koji Murofushi]] of [[Japan]], with [[Ivan Tsikhan]] of [[Belarus]] taking the silver, and [[Esref Apak]] of [[Turkey]] taking the bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web | last =Agence France Presse | title =Hammer throw champion stripped of gold | work =ABC News Online| date =[[August 25]], [[2004]] | url =http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200408/s1187614.htm
| accessdate =2008-05-05}}</ref> 
Finally, [[Ireland|Irish]] [[equestrian]] [[Cian O'Connor]] was stripped of his gold medal in [[Equestrian at the 2004 Summer Olympics - Individual jumping|individual jumping]] due to the doping of his horse, Waterford Crystal, resulting in the title being awarded to [[Rodrigo Pessoa]] of [[Brazil]], the silver medal to [[Chris Kappler]] of the United States, and the bronze medal to [[Marco Kutscher]] of Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2005/0327/oconnorc.html |title=O'Connor loses Olympic gold medal |publisher=RT<U+00C9> |accessdate=2008-05-05 |date=2005-03-27}}</ref>

==Medal count==

The ranking in this table is based on information provided by the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name="medal count"/> In [[boxing]] and [[judo]], two bronze medals were awarded in each weight class, so the total number of bronze medals is greater than the total number of gold and silver medals.<ref name="olympic.org"/>

The ranking sorts by the number of gold medals earned by a country (in this context a country is an entity represented by a National Olympic Committee). The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals. If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically. The host country, Greece, is highlighted in lavender. The greatest number of medals won in each medal category, gold, silver, bronze, and total, is in boldface.

